<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="35" pageNumber="34">
The genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24919" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Baracidris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Baracidris Bolton" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Baracidris</taxonomicName>
includes three small species (one undescribed) which are litter inhabitants in Central and Western Africa. Although the genus is easily isolated from the other African myrmicines, this is a more difficult task regarding the World fauna. The combination of characters (median portion of the clypeus as narrow fringe, antennae 12 segmented with club 2 segmented, reduced palps, metapleural lobes larger than in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2325" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Adelomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Adelomyrmex Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Adelomyrmex</taxonomicName>
, petiole and postpetiole subcylindric) separates this genus from all other myrmicines, although currently we lack synapomorphic features for 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24919" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Baracidris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Baracidris Bolton" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Baracidris</taxonomicName>
. We maintain this genus primarily upon its geographical distribution.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
